[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":2149},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Falgorithm\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F04\u002Ffizzbuzz-for-javascript\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Falgorithm\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F04\u002Ffizzbuzz-for-javascript\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Falgorithm\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F04\u002Ffizzbuzz-for-javascript\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Falgorithm\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F04\u002Ffizzbuzz-for-javascript\u002F":2135,"related:\u002Fen\u002Falgorithm\u002F2025\u002F02\u002F04\u002Ffizzbuzz-for-javascript\u002F":2144},"\u002Falgorithm\u002F20250204\u002F3664816602\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":2120,"date":2121,"description":2122,"extension":2123,"lang":2124,"meta":2125,"navigation":396,"path":2126,"readingMinutes":711,"seo":2127,"standalone":2128,"stem":2129,"tags":2130,"tldr":2132,"updated":2121,"url":2133,"__hash__":2134},"content\u002Fen\u002FAlgorithm\u002Ffizzbuzz-for-javascript.md","FizzBuzz for JavaScript","6648166020",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":2107},"minimark",[11,18,23,26,30,33,36,62,65,105,117,120,123,126,129,202,205,210,217,306,311,320,324,333,358,416,422,428,431,451,460,578,583,592,695,700,719,723,734,873,878,882,893,896,907,925,935,951,961,975,978,1161,1166,1194,1374,1379,1382,1386,1389,1396,1399,1403,1406,1623,1630,1829,1832,2059,2062,2100,2103],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":6,"src":17},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Falgorithm\u002Ffizzbuzz\u002FFizzBuzz_for_JavaScript_banner%20.webp",[19,20,22],"h2",{"id":21},"intro","Intro",[12,24,25],{},"FizzBuzz is actually a game, but it also gets used as a coding interview question — especially at companies like Google and Facebook, which use FizzBuzz to test basic programming skills. So it makes for a great practice problem.",[19,27,29],{"id":28},"quick-fizzbuzz-intro","Quick FizzBuzz intro",[12,31,32],{},"A lot of folks have heard of FizzBuzz, but if you haven't, no worries. FizzBuzz is a simple math game, and it shows up widely in coding interviews. If you're job-hunting, I'd really recommend understanding what FizzBuzz is and what the rules are.",[12,34,35],{},"The rules:",[37,38,39,47,53,59],"ol",{},[40,41,42,43],"li",{},"If the number is divisible by 3, output ",[44,45,46],"code",{},"Fizz",[40,48,49,50],{},"If the number is divisible by 5, output ",[44,51,52],{},"Buzz",[40,54,55,56],{},"If the number is divisible by both 3 and 5, output ",[44,57,58],{},"FizzBuzz",[40,60,61],{},"If none of the above match, output the number itself",[12,63,64],{},"So based on those rules, gameplay looks like:",[37,66,67,70,76,82,91,97],{},[40,68,69],{},"A group of players sit in a circle",[40,71,72,73],{},"Starting from the first player, they say ",[44,74,75],{},"1",[40,77,78,79],{},"The second player says ",[44,80,81],{},"2",[40,83,84,85,87,88],{},"The third player says ",[44,86,46],{},", not ",[44,89,90],{},"3",[40,92,93,94],{},"The fourth player says ",[44,95,96],{},"4",[40,98,99,100,87,102],{},"The fifth player says ",[44,101,52],{},[44,103,104],{},"5",[12,106,107,108,111,112,87,114,116],{},"And so on. When you reach ",[44,109,110],{},"15",", the player says ",[44,113,58],{},[44,115,110],{},".",[12,118,119],{},"That's the FizzBuzz rules.",[19,121,6],{"id":122},"fizzbuzz-for-javascript",[12,124,125],{},"Applied to programming, the common interview question is:",[12,127,128],{},"\"Write a FizzBuzz function. When passed a number, return the FizzBuzz result. The input will be between 1 and 100.\"",[130,131,136],"pre",{"className":132,"code":133,"language":134,"meta":135,"style":135},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","FizzBuzz(1); \u002F\u002F 1\nFizzBuzz(3); \u002F\u002F Fizz\nFizzBuzz(5); \u002F\u002F Buzz\nFizzBuzz(15); \u002F\u002F FizzBuzz\n","js","",[44,137,138,160,174,188],{"__ignoreMap":135},[139,140,143,146,150,153,156],"span",{"class":141,"line":142},"line",1,[139,144,58],{"class":145},"scAaK",[139,147,149],{"class":148},"s8XSl","(",[139,151,75],{"class":152},"stw71",[139,154,155],{"class":148},"); ",[139,157,159],{"class":158},"sGBqm","\u002F\u002F 1\n",[139,161,163,165,167,169,171],{"class":141,"line":162},2,[139,164,58],{"class":145},[139,166,149],{"class":148},[139,168,90],{"class":152},[139,170,155],{"class":148},[139,172,173],{"class":158},"\u002F\u002F Fizz\n",[139,175,177,179,181,183,185],{"class":141,"line":176},3,[139,178,58],{"class":145},[139,180,149],{"class":148},[139,182,104],{"class":152},[139,184,155],{"class":148},[139,186,187],{"class":158},"\u002F\u002F Buzz\n",[139,189,191,193,195,197,199],{"class":141,"line":190},4,[139,192,58],{"class":145},[139,194,149],{"class":148},[139,196,110],{"class":152},[139,198,155],{"class":148},[139,200,201],{"class":158},"\u002F\u002F FizzBuzz\n",[12,203,204],{},"Based on this and the FizzBuzz rules, we can break this into steps:",[206,207,209],"h3",{"id":208},"step-1-set-up-the-fizzbuzz-function","Step 1: Set up the FizzBuzz function",[12,211,212,213,216],{},"Since we'll be passed a number between 1 and 100, we'll need a loop. Use a ",[44,214,215],{},"for"," loop to iterate 1 to 100:",[130,218,220],{"className":132,"code":219,"language":134,"meta":135,"style":135},"const FizzBuzz = (num) => {\n  for (let i = 1; i \u003C= num; i++) {\n    console.log(i);\n  }\n};\n",[44,221,222,250,284,295,300],{"__ignoreMap":135},[139,223,224,228,231,234,237,241,244,247],{"class":141,"line":142},[139,225,227],{"class":226},"sOudu","const",[139,229,230],{"class":145}," FizzBuzz",[139,232,233],{"class":226}," =",[139,235,236],{"class":148}," (",[139,238,240],{"class":239},"syBk-","num",[139,242,243],{"class":148},") ",[139,245,246],{"class":226},"=>",[139,248,249],{"class":148}," {\n",[139,251,252,255,257,260,263,266,269,272,275,278,281],{"class":141,"line":162},[139,253,254],{"class":226},"  for",[139,256,236],{"class":148},[139,258,259],{"class":226},"let",[139,261,262],{"class":148}," i ",[139,264,265],{"class":226},"=",[139,267,268],{"class":152}," 1",[139,270,271],{"class":148},"; i ",[139,273,274],{"class":226},"\u003C=",[139,276,277],{"class":148}," num; i",[139,279,280],{"class":226},"++",[139,282,283],{"class":148},") {\n",[139,285,286,289,292],{"class":141,"line":176},[139,287,288],{"class":148},"    console.",[139,290,291],{"class":145},"log",[139,293,294],{"class":148},"(i);\n",[139,296,297],{"class":141,"line":190},[139,298,299],{"class":148},"  }\n",[139,301,303],{"class":141,"line":302},5,[139,304,305],{"class":148},"};\n",[12,307,308],{},[15,309],{"alt":58,"src":310},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Falgorithm\u002Ffizzbuzz\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202025-02-05%2022.52.11.png",[12,312,313,314,316,317,319],{},"Step 1 is the simple part — define a ",[44,315,58],{}," function and run a ",[44,318,215],{}," loop from 1 to 100.",[206,321,323],{"id":322},"step-2-check-if-its-a-multiple-of-3","Step 2: Check if it's a multiple of 3",[12,325,326,327,329,330,116],{},"Next, we need to check if the number is a multiple of 3. If so, return ",[44,328,46],{},". How do we check for divisibility by 3? Use the modulo operator ",[44,331,332],{},"%",[12,334,335,336,338,339,341,342,345,346,349,350,353,354,357],{},"What's ",[44,337,332],{},"? ",[44,340,332],{}," is the modulo (or remainder) operator. Usage is simple — ",[44,343,344],{},"a % b"," returns ",[44,347,348],{},"0"," when ",[44,351,352],{},"a"," is divisible by ",[44,355,356],{},"b",", otherwise it returns the remainder. For example:",[130,359,361],{"className":132,"code":360,"language":134,"meta":135,"style":135},"const a = 5;\nconst b = 3;\n\nconsole.log(a % b); \u002F\u002F 2\n",[44,362,363,378,392,398],{"__ignoreMap":135},[139,364,365,367,370,372,375],{"class":141,"line":142},[139,366,227],{"class":226},[139,368,369],{"class":152}," a",[139,371,233],{"class":226},[139,373,374],{"class":152}," 5",[139,376,377],{"class":148},";\n",[139,379,380,382,385,387,390],{"class":141,"line":162},[139,381,227],{"class":226},[139,383,384],{"class":152}," b",[139,386,233],{"class":226},[139,388,389],{"class":152}," 3",[139,391,377],{"class":148},[139,393,394],{"class":141,"line":176},[139,395,397],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":396},true,"\n",[139,399,400,403,405,408,410,413],{"class":141,"line":190},[139,401,402],{"class":148},"console.",[139,404,291],{"class":145},[139,406,407],{"class":148},"(a ",[139,409,332],{"class":226},[139,411,412],{"class":148}," b); ",[139,414,415],{"class":158},"\u002F\u002F 2\n",[12,417,418],{},[15,419],{"alt":420,"src":421},"modulo operator","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Falgorithm\u002Ffizzbuzz\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202025-02-05%2022.55.19.png",[12,423,424,425,427],{},"Why ",[44,426,81],{},"? Think of it like having 5 apples and trying to split them among 3 people. Everyone gets 1 apple, and 2 are left over — those 2 are the remainder.",[12,429,430],{},"In terms of the math: split it into quotient and remainder:",[432,433,434,444],"ul",{},[40,435,436,437,440,441,443],{},"Quotient: ",[44,438,439],{},"5 \u002F 3 = 1.6666666666666667",", take the integer part ",[44,442,75],{}," — each person gets 1 apple",[40,445,446,447,450],{},"Remainder: ",[44,448,449],{},"5 - 3 × 1 = 2"," — that's the remainder, the leftover apples",[12,452,453,454,456,457,459],{},"Now that we get how modulo works, back to Fizz. When the number is divisible by 3, we return ",[44,455,46],{}," — using ",[44,458,332],{},":",[130,461,463],{"className":132,"code":462,"language":134,"meta":135,"style":135},"const FizzBuzz = (num) => {\n  for (let i = 1; i \u003C= num; i++) {\n    if (i % 3 === 0) {\n      console.log('Fizz');\n    } else {\n      console.log(i);\n    }\n  }\n};\n",[44,464,465,483,507,527,543,553,562,568,573],{"__ignoreMap":135},[139,466,467,469,471,473,475,477,479,481],{"class":141,"line":142},[139,468,227],{"class":226},[139,470,230],{"class":145},[139,472,233],{"class":226},[139,474,236],{"class":148},[139,476,240],{"class":239},[139,478,243],{"class":148},[139,480,246],{"clas